<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> is up to us to help those folks think through the issue. If we view our religiously-minded, pro-Bush fellow-citizens as enemies to be defeated, they will only stiffen their backs and rally round the president. But if we view them as our partners in a shared political life, people we have to talk with constructively, they might just listen. They might just understand that it is not only dangerous to let God tell the president when and where to strike. It is just plain un-American. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So it is Un-American to listen to God?  Is it also Un-American to worship God?  ANY God?  <br>
<br>
Now I am not talking about hearing voices commanded down from the heavens, but I am talking about a more fundamental belief system, living by the words of religion.  Muslims live by the fundamental words of their religion.  They beleive that it is ok to act for their state, people, etc in the name of their God.  Our motto on our coins is, &quot;In God we trust&quot;.  People do remember the words, &quot;one nation, under God, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all&quot; don't they?  <br>
<br>
Is it only ok to be guided by a spiritual belief system, as long as it is hidden.  Is a religious man expected to hide his religion?  Is that not everything we have been taught against in church since we were babes?<br>
<br>
Something else.  This professor goes on to say...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>When the president lets God tell him what to do, it violates the spirit of democracy. In a democracy, it is the people, not God, who make the decisions. The president is supposed to represent the will of the people. Yes, he must seek the best advice he can get and use his own best judgment. That means relying on facts, intelligent analysis, and rational thought-not divine inspiration. Once the president lets God's voice replace the human mind, we are back in the Middle Ages, back in the very situation our revolution was supposed to get us out of. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Am I to beleive that believing in God, following a faith, is going to be the downfall of democracy?  Am I to beleive that God, has no influence over the people and their moral character?  Or do people actually beleive that religion and God are just some Sunday morning thing you do once or twice a month before Football starts?  <br>
<br>
God is going to take us back into the Middle-Ages?  I boggle at the thought of thinking how that could happen.  Men throughout the modern era have been guided by spiritual thinking, religion and the church and have led this society and world into its current path.  I would think god has led us out of the middle ages, by providing the ability for man to think and be kind and considerate of his neighbors.  It was men like Adolph Hitler, a man without religion and love in his heart that did things to destroy what we became.  Granted, their have been fanatics on all sides, but I highly doubt the current situation holds tea.<br>
<br>
The profound insight that hit me first was that this was a professor of religion: Ira Chernus is Professor of Religious Studies at the University of Colorado at Boulder.  And to make statements like this, just dumbfounds me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If Bush lets God make foreign policy decisions, is he violating not just the spirit but the letter of the law? The Constitution gives him the right to make foreign policy. It does not say what should or should not go through his mind in the process. It certainly does not forbid him from consulting God. But it does protect us from having any religious belief determine our laws and policies. Did Bush violate the First Amendment's separation of church and state? The answer is not totally clear.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So now, we are to impeach a president for having a religion?  Or all of our leaders supposed to be unspiritual mindless, NON-thinkers, that only bow to the will of the next poll.  This professor says no religious belief determine our laws and policies.  In plan this is true, in reality it is false.  Common laws of the church form most basic laws of society, acts against murder, robbery, etc.  I suspect our early leaders would be shocked at that statement.  I suppose that they would even be outraged that a person could think that religious beliefs, the foundation for modern society, hold no sway on the ethics of modern man.  And it should be a violation of law, to follow a doctrine of religion?  <br>
