<br>
Even if we want to set aside the notion of seperation of church and state, which goes back a VERY VERY long time, you run into the question of why should any 1 religion have it's doctrine forced down the throats of every other american, simply because the president happens to be OF that religion?<br>
<br>
Even among the christian community, EVERYONE has a different idea of who/what god is and what is taught. Hell, just compare, say, southern baptists and the episcopalians, who are about to elect an openly gay bishop. So, who's god is right, and who should EVER be allowed to decide that for OTHER people?<br>
<br>
Personally, I happen to be Pagan (feri tradition wicca, to be specific.) Parents are catholic, I got raised that way, decided  I had strong fundamental differences with some of the tenets of catholicism, so I found my own path. Why should someone like me, or indeed ANYONE who doesn't happen to be a fundamentalist christian be forced to follow the moral teachings of that religion? (ps, threatening me with hell for not believing in god just causes me much humor. If I don't believe in the overall judeo-christian structure, I obviously don't believe in hell, so why would I be concerned about a place I feel doesn't exist?)<br>
<br>
Should a president who happened to be Hindu be allowed to ban the eating of Beef in the country? How about a Buddhist president banning the eating of ALL meat? How about a Satanist president requiring weekly ritual orgies? Or should people who AREN'T christian be banned from holding office? Boy yeah, *THAT* would be a plan, huh?<br>
<br>
Obviously, none of the above are likely or would be good things to happen. However, why then should EVERYONE be forced into following whatever mores and values that Bush's brand of christianity follows? Its no different in *ANY* way than any of the examples I gave above. It is never right, never proper, and *ALWAYS* wrong for someone to have another's religion forced upon them.<br>
<br>
